<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="305" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,821,1137]" pageId="2" pageNumber="305">
<taxonomicName box="[199,442,858,881]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="305" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aripuanensis">
<emphasis box="[199,442,858,881]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="305">Bittacus aripuanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Pictet" authorityYear="1836" box="[495,630,857,882]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="305" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="blancheti">
<emphasis box="[495,630,857,882]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="305">B. blancheti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were the two species previously placed in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Esben-Petersen (Penny" authorityYear="1977" box="[1220,1354,857,882]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Neobittacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="305" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1220,1354,857,882]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="305">Neobittacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which was characterized by the large number of costal crossveins in the forewing. This character, however, is quite variable, as discussed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Machado, R. J. P. &amp; Godoi, F. S. P. &amp; Rafael, J. A." box="[442,699,929,954]" pageId="2" pageNumber="305" pagination="27 - 38" refId="ref15417" refString="Machado, R. J. P., Godoi, F. S. P. &amp; Rafael, J. A. (2009) Neotropical Mecoptera (Insecta): new generic synonymies, new combinations, key to families and genera, and checklist of species. Zootaxa, 2148, 27 - 38." type="journal article" year="2009">
Machado 
<emphasis box="[556,614,929,954]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="305">et al.</emphasis>
(2009)
</bibRefCitation>
, who synonymized it with 
<taxonomicName box="[1012,1104,930,953]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Bittacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="305" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1012,1104,930,953]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="305">Bittacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. For the same reason, 
<bibRefCitation author="Navas, L." pageId="2" pageNumber="305" pagination="354 - 389" refId="ref15675" refString="Navas, L. (1929) Insectos exoticos neuropteros y afines del Museo civico de Genova. Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale Giacomo Doria, 53, 354 - 389." type="journal article" year="1929">Navás (1929)</bibRefCitation>
had synonymized 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Esben-Petersen (Penny" authorityYear="1977" box="[437,571,965,990]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Neobittacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="305" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[437,571,965,990]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="305">Neobittacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1908" box="[635,755,965,990]" class="Insecta" family="Bittacidae" genus="Thyridates" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Mecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="305" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[635,755,965,990]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="305">Thyridates</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The species seems to be restricted to the southern border of the Amazon and can be easily identified by the maculation pattern of the wings and the general shape of the male epandrium.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
